com.martinandersson.money.unittest

Class ChronicleMapTest

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.martinandersson.money.unittest.ChronicleMapTest

  • public class ChronicleMapTest
extends java.lang.Object
    Will unit test the full life-cycle of a Chronicle Map backed by a file on disk.

    Most test methods will build a map, read all AppleData and put these entities in a Chronicle Map. Then, read all entities back from the map.

    Each test print statistics in terms of key/value byte sizes, time cost for put() and get(), but most importantly (for me at least), the actual file size that results from serializing all 8961 prices contained in AppleData.

    Parameterized test methods that accept a SerializationFramework are split based on Price implementation.

    Chronicle Map can be configured to use a custom marshaller for keys and values. Parameterized tests are executed for each serialization framework used in this project (see serializer()).

    JavaDoc that refer to "worst" versus "best" serialization framework judge file size only (as noted on my machine). For all price implementations, not using a serialization framework (Chronicle Map default) used most disk space. The winner was Kryo (with custom Kryo serializers).

    Time cost is irrelevant for the purpose of comparison, but speaking of file sizes, it might be interesting to know that I run Windows 10, NTFS.

    Please note that time performance of Chronicle Map is more accurately benchmarked in ChronicleMapBaselineBenchmark and ChronicleMapRealBenchmark.

        It's interesting to note that PriceSerialization.test_customFastMoney2() report an exact byte size of 97. This test see an exact byte size of 22.

        If the explanation was that the currency code String object is "reused", then we would have seen the same effect for the previous test case using CustomFastMoneyPrice1 - but, we don't.

        It's also odd that the value - which contains both a date (key) and money information - is actually smaller then just the key (one date).
